{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "BackgroundColorectal cancer (CRC) is a significant public health concern, with various social determinants playing a crucial role in its incidence, diagnosis, treatment, and outcomes.",
    "Recent recognition of the increase in early onset CRC makes improving screening follow-through an important public health concern [1].",
    "As with screening for other diseases, adherence to CRC screening recommendations is crucial for early detection and prevention of the disease [2].",
    "Research has shown that social and demographic factors such as education, age, income, and healthcare access influence the utilization of CRC screening tests [3].Stressful life events, such as divorce, marriage, or sudden loss of job, have a unique role as additional social determinants of health [4] as they span all aspects of life and may occur regardless of a patient's social and economic status.",
    "However, populations with lower socioeconomic status are more vulnerable to adverse life events [5]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Recent recognition of the increase in early onset CRC makes improving screening follow-through an important public health concern [1].",
